+---
+---
+
+# CVE-2026-41071 — False Positive for Debian 12 (Bookworm)
+
+| Field                 | Value                                                                                                      |
+|-----------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
+| **CVE ID**            | CVE-2026-41071                                                                                             |
+| **Component**         | libheif                                                                                                    |
+| **CWE**               | CWE-125: Out-of-bounds Read (heap-buffer-overflow)                                                          |
+| **Distribution**      | Debian 12 (Bookworm)                                                                                       |
+| **Bookworm package**  | `libheif` source package, version `1.15.1-1` / `1.15.1-1+deb12u1` (security/point-release respins on the 1.15.1 base) |
+| **Upstream affected** | libheif ≤ 1.21.2 *that ship `SampleAuxInfoReader` / the sequences-track subsystem* (introduced in 1.20.0)   |
+| **Upstream fixed in** | libheif 1.22.0 (commit `f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d`)                                          |
+| **Assessment**        | **FALSE POSITIVE for Bookworm — package is not vulnerable, no patch required.**                            |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Why this CVE is being flagged
+
+Scanners (Trivy, Grype, OSV-Scanner, Anchore, etc.) and the Debian security tracker match this CVE against any package whose version compares as `<= 1.21.2`. The Bookworm package version `1.15.1-1` satisfies that comparison, so it is flagged.
+
+The [Debian security tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2026-41071) currently lists Bookworm (`1.15.1-1+deb12u1`) as *vulnerable*, but this is the **default "open" state applied automatically to every version at or below the fixed release** — it is not a code-level determination.
+
+**Version comparison alone is incorrect here.** The CVE describes a defect in a specific function — the `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor in the image-**sequences** subsystem — and neither that function, that file, nor the entire sequences/track feature exists in the 1.15.1 source tree shipped by Bookworm. The advisory's "≤ 1.21.2" range therefore produces a false match against 1.15.1.
+
+## 2. Why Bookworm's libheif 1.15.1 is not vulnerable
+
+The CVE describes an out-of-bounds read in the construction of a `SampleAuxInfoReader`, while parsing the Sample Auxiliary Information Size (`saiz`) box of a HEIF **sequence/track**:
+
+```cpp
+// libheif/sequences/track.cc — DOES NOT EXIST IN 1.15.1
+SampleAuxInfoReader::SampleAuxInfoReader(...) {
+    ...
+    // iterates saiz->get_num_samples() times without checking it
+    // against the size of the chunk table; current_chunk walks past
+    // chunks.size() for a crafted file  -->  OOB read on `chunks`
+    assert(current_chunk < chunks.size());   // pre-fix
+    ...
+}
+```
+
+The fix (`f20c817`) adds two guards: a bounds check that breaks out of the loop when `current_chunk >= chunks.size()`, and a validation in `Track::load()` that rejects the file when `saiz->get_num_samples() > m_stsz->num_samples()` ("Number of samples in 'saiz' box exceeds actual number of samples.").
+
+For this bug to be reachable, **all of the following must be true** in the deployed source:
+
+1. The image-**sequences** subsystem exists (reading/writing of `trak`/`moov`-style timed tracks inside HEIF).
+2. `libheif/sequences/track.cc` and the `Track` class exist.
+3. Sample Auxiliary Information (`saiz`/`saio`) parsing exists, i.e. the `SampleAuxInfoReader` class.
+4. A crafted file can drive `current_chunk` past `chunks.size()` because the per-sample loop trusts `saiz->get_num_samples()`.
+
+In libheif 1.15.1 **none of those preconditions are met**. The entire sequences/track feature — and with it all `saiz`/SAI handling — was not present yet.
+
+### 2.1 Direct evidence — the file and symbols do not exist
+
+Verified against this checkout (libheif `1.15.1`, commit `06f6acfe`):
+
+```
+$ git ls-tree -r HEAD --name-only | grep -iE 'sequences|track\.cc|saiz|saio'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+```
+$ git grep -nE 'SampleAuxInfoReader|get_num_samples|fourcc\("saiz"\)|class Track' HEAD -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+There is no `libheif/sequences/` directory, no `track.cc`, no `SampleAuxInfoReader` symbol, no `saiz`/`saio` box parser, and no track/sequence decode path anywhere in the Bookworm source. (A broad `git grep` for `track` matches only the unrelated bundled test framework `tests/catch.hpp`.)
+
+### 2.2 Upstream history — when the vulnerable code actually landed
+
+| Upstream milestone | What it added                                                                                  | First tagged release |
+|--------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------|
+| Sequences API      | Introduced the entire image-sequences subsystem, track reading/writing, and Sample Auxiliary Information (SAI / `saiz` / `saio`), incl. `SampleAuxInfoReader` | **1.20.0**           |
+| `f20c817`          | The CVE-2026-41071 fix (bounds check in `SampleAuxInfoReader` + `saiz` sample-count validation in `Track::load`) | **1.22.0**           |
+
+Bookworm shipped from the 1.15.1 base, which predates the sequences API (1.20.0) by **five minor releases**. The vulnerable function literally did not exist when 1.15.1 was tagged.
+
+### 2.3 Runtime behaviour with a malicious sequence file
+
+When libheif 1.15.1 encounters a HEIF/MP4-style file containing image-sequence tracks with a malformed `saiz` box:
+
+- 1.15.1 has no sequence/track reader at all. There is no code that opens `trak`/`moov` timed tracks, no code that parses `saiz`/`saio`, and therefore no `SampleAuxInfoReader` to mis-construct.
+- The out-of-bounds read on the `chunks` vector cannot occur because the loop that performs it does not exist.
+
+A crafted proof-of-concept that triggers the OOB read on 1.21.x will, on Bookworm's 1.15.1, never reach any sequence-parsing code.
+
+## 3. How to verify locally
+
+```
+# Confirm the package version
+$ dpkg-query -W -f='${Version}\n' libheif1
+1.15.1-1                      # (or 1.15.1-1+deb12u1, a point-release on the same base)
+
+# Confirm the source has no sequences/track subsystem
+$ apt-get source libheif
+$ cd libheif-1.15.1
+$ find . -iname '*track*' -o -iname '*sequence*'   # no results
+$ grep -RE 'SampleAuxInfoReader|fourcc\("saiz"\)' .  # no results
+$ grep -RE 'class Track' .                           # no results
+```
+
+If those searches return empty, the binary cannot contain the vulnerable code path.
+
+## 4. Recommended action
+
+- **Do not patch.** There is nothing to patch — the function being fixed, and the entire subsystem it lives in, do not exist in this source tree.
+- **Mark as not-affected in the SBOM / vulnerability tracker.** Suggested fields:
+  - `status`: `not_affected`
+  - `justification`: `vulnerable_code_not_present`
+  - `impact_statement`: "libheif 1.15.1 (Bookworm) predates the introduction of the HEIF image-sequences/track subsystem and its Sample Auxiliary Information (`saiz`) parsing. The vulnerable `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor was first added in upstream 1.20.0 (sequences API). Neither the class, the file `libheif/sequences/track.cc`, nor any `saiz` decode path exists in this version, so the out-of-bounds read is unreachable."
+- **Suppress in scanners.** Example (VEX / OpenVEX-style):
+  ```json
+  {
+    "vulnerability": "CVE-2026-41071",
+    "products": ["pkg:deb/debian/libheif@1.15.1-1?distro=bookworm"],
+    "status": "not_affected",
+    "justification": "vulnerable_code_not_present"
+  }
+  ```
+  For Trivy specifically, this can also be expressed via a `.trivyignore` entry with a justification comment, but a VEX document is preferred because it is machine-readable and survives scanner upgrades.
+
+> **Note on Debian patch series:** this assessment is based on the upstream 1.15.1 source. Debian's `1.15.1-1+deb12u1` carries a small patch series; it is extremely unlikely (and was not observed in any release note) that a security point-release would backport the entire 1.20.0 sequences subsystem. If absolute rigour is required, confirm by unpacking the `.debian.tar.xz` and checking that no patch introduces `libheif/sequences/` or `SampleAuxInfoReader`.
+
+## 5. References
+
+- Upstream fix commit: https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/commit/f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d
+- Upstream introduction of the sequences API / SAI (`saiz`) handling: libheif **1.20.0** release — https://github.com/strukturag/libheif/releases/tag/v1.20.0
+- CVE record: https://vulnerability.circl.lu/vuln/cve-2026-41071
+- Debian security tracker: https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2026-41071
+- Debian Bookworm libheif package: https://packages.debian.org/bookworm/libheif1
