+| **Distribution**      | Debian 12 (Bookworm)                                                                              |
+| **Bookworm package**  | `libheif` source package, version `1.15.1-1` (and security/point-release respins on the 1.15.1 base) |
+| **Upstream affected** | libheif ≤ 1.21.2 *that ship `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()`* (introduced in 1.17.0)         |
+| **Upstream fixed in** | libheif 1.22.0 (commit `12369427`)                                                                |
+| **Assessment**        | **FALSE POSITIVE for Bookworm — package is not vulnerable, no patch required.**                    |
+
+---
+
+## 1. Why this CVE is being flagged
+
+Scanners (Trivy, Grype, OSV-Scanner, Anchore, etc.) match this CVE against any package whose version compares as `<= 1.21.2`. The Bookworm package version `1.15.1-1` satisfies that comparison, so scanners flag it.
+
+However, **version comparison alone is incorrect here**. The CVE describes a defect in a specific function — `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` — and that function does not exist in the 1.15.1 source tree shipped by Bookworm. Scanners that rely purely on the upstream advisory's "≤ 1.21.2" range generate a false match.
+
+## 2. Why Bookworm's libheif 1.15.1 is not vulnerable
+
+The CVE describes a heap buffer overflow inside:
+
+```cpp
+// libheif/image-items/mask_image.cc — DOES NOT EXIST IN 1.15.1
+Error MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image(...) {
+    ...
+    if (((uint32_t)stride) == width) {
+        memcpy(dst, data.data(), data.size());   // <-- overflow
+    }
+    ...
+}
+```
+
+For this bug to be reachable, **all of the following must be true** in the deployed source:
+
+1. The `MaskImageCodec` class exists.
+2. `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` exists and is dispatched for items of fourcc type `mski`.
+3. The decoder reads `mskC` (mask configuration) and `ispe` (image spatial extent) properties.
+4. There is a single-`memcpy` fast-path branch sized by `data.size()` (attacker-controlled).
+
+In libheif 1.15.1 **none of those preconditions are met**. The entire HEIF "mask image" (`mski`) feature was not present yet.
+
+### 2.1 Direct evidence — the file does not exist
+
+```
+$ git ls-tree -r v1.15.1 --name-only | grep -i mask
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+```
+$ git grep -nE "MaskImage|decode_mask|mskC|fourcc\\(\"mski\"\\)" v1.15.1 -- '*.cc' '*.h'
+(empty — no results)
+```
+
+There is no `mask_image.cc`, no `mask_image.h`, no `MaskImageCodec` symbol, no `mski` fourcc handler, and no `mskC` property parser anywhere in the Bookworm source.
+
+### 2.2 Upstream history — when the vulnerable code actually landed
+
+| Upstream commit | What it added                                                                            | First tagged release |
+|-----------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------|
+| `94f9a09e`      | Created `libheif/codecs/mask_image.{cc,h}` and `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()`     | **1.17.0**           |
+| `b6a77bff`      | Wired the inline `if (stride == width) memcpy(dst, data.data(), data.size())` fast path | **1.19.0**           |
+| `e127d201`      | Moved codecs into `libheif/image-items/` (the path named in the CVE patch)               | post-1.17 refactor   |
+| `12369427`      | The CVE-2026-32741 fix                                                                   | **1.22.0**           |
+
+Bookworm shipped from the 1.15.1 base, which predates `94f9a09e` by two minor releases. The vulnerable function literally did not exist when 1.15.1 was tagged.
+
+### 2.3 Runtime behaviour with a malicious `mski` file
+
+When libheif 1.15.1 encounters a HEIF container whose primary item or a referenced item has fourcc `mski`:
+
+- `HeifContext::interpret_heif_file()` does not recognise the item type as a decodable image and either returns an "unsupported feature" `heif_error_Unsupported_feature` or — for files where `mski` is only referenced — silently ignores the reference.
+- No `memcpy` of attacker-controlled length occurs because the code path that performs that copy has not been written yet.
+
+A crafted proof-of-concept HEIF that triggers the overflow on 1.22.x will, on Bookworm's 1.15.1, simply fail to decode.
+
+## 3. How to verify locally
+
+```
+# Confirm the package version
+$ dpkg-query -W -f='${Version}\n' libheif1
+1.15.1-1
+# (or a Debian point-release variant on the same 1.15.1 base)
+
+# Confirm the source has no mask-image codec
+$ apt-get source libheif
+$ cd libheif-1.15.1
+$ find . -iname '*mask*'                       # no results
+$ grep -RE "MaskImage|decode_mask|mskC" .       # no results
+$ grep -RE 'fourcc\("mski"\)' .                 # no results
+```
+
+If the three searches above return empty, the binary cannot contain the vulnerable code path.
+
+## 4. Recommended action
+
+- **Do not patch.** There is nothing to patch — the function being fixed does not exist in this source tree.
+- **Mark as not-affected in the SBOM / vulnerability tracker.** Suggested fields:
+  - `status`: `not_affected`
+  - `justification`: `vulnerable_code_not_present`
+  - `impact_statement`: "libheif 1.15.1 (Bookworm) predates the introduction of HEIF mask-image (`mski`) decoding. The vulnerable function `MaskImageCodec::decode_mask_image()` was first added in upstream 1.17.0; the specific memcpy branch fixed by the advisory was added in 1.19.0. Neither the function nor any `mski` decode path exists in this version, so the heap buffer overflow is unreachable."
+- **Suppress in scanners.** Example (VEX / OpenVEX-style):
+  ```json
+  {
+    "vulnerability": "CVE-2026-32741",
+    "products": ["pkg:deb/debian/libheif@1.15.1-1?distro=bookworm"],
+    "status": "not_affected",
+    "justification": "vulnerable_code_not_present"
+  }
+  ```
+  For Trivy specifically, this can also be expressed via a `.trivyignore` entry with a justification comment, but a VEX document is preferred because it is machine-readable and survives scanner upgrades.
+
